{"id":"1108.0963","submitter":"Haixing Miao","authors":"Huan Yang, Haixing Miao, Yanbei Chen","title":"Non-adiabatic elimination of auxiliary modes in continuous quantum\n  measurements","comments":"a revised version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.85.040101","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  When measuring a complex quantum system, we are often interested in only a\nfew degrees of freedom-the plant, while the rest of them are collected as\nauxiliary modes-the bath. The bath can have finite memory (non-Markovian), and\nsimply ignoring its dynamics, i.e., adiabatically eliminating it, will prevent\nus from predicting the true quantum behavior of the plant. We generalize the\ntechnique introduced by Strunz et. al. [Phys. Rev. Lett 82, 1801 (1999)], and\ndevelop a formalism that allows us to eliminate the bath non-adiabatically in\ncontinuous quantum measurements, and obtain a non-Markovian stochastic master\nequation for the plant which we focus on. We apply this formalism to three\ninteresting examples relevant to current experiments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2011 23:34:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 5 Aug 2011 01:29:51 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 31 Aug 2011 02:45:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-30"}
